{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653066"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18557"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18557"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0,0.96,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75661"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11289"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7682"},{"type":"tags","id":"10813"},{"type":"tags","id":"10824"},{"type":"tags","id":"10825"},{"type":"tags","id":"10826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26174"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75661"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA laboratory technician is preparing to examine a clinical specimen using microscopy. The specimen requires identification of the basic structural characteristics of any potential pathogenic organisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following staining techniques is most useful for identifying bacteria based on their cell wall characteristics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["India ink stain","Methylene blue stain","Calcofluor white stain","Gram stain","Giemsa stain"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EGram stain\u003C/strong\u003E is the most useful initial staining technique for identifying bacteria based on their cell wall characteristics. It differentiates bacteria into gram-positive (purple) and gram-negative (pink) based on their ability to retain the crystal violet-iodine complex after alcohol decolourisation. Some bacterial strains retain the stain due to fundamental differences in cell wall structure as the stain adheres to the thick peptidoglycan layer of the cell wall in Gram-positive bacteria, which is absent in gram-negative bacteria. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethylene blue stain\u003C/strong\u003E is a simple stain that colours all bacteria blue but does not differentiate between cell wall types\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiemsa stain\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for blood parasites and does not provide information about bacterial cell wall structure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndia ink stain\u003C/strong\u003E is a negative staining technique used to visualize capsules around organisms like \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcofluor white stain\u003C/strong\u003E is a fluorescent stain specific for fungal cell walls containing chitin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Gram stain remains the cornerstone of bacterial identification in clinical microbiology, providing rapid preliminary information to guide empiric antimicrobial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gram staining differentiates bacteria based on cell wall structure, with gram-positive bacteria retaining crystal violet-iodine complex and appearing purple.","Gram negative bacteria appear pink when stained with Gram stain."],"references":["Murray PR, Rosenthal KS, Pfaller MA. Medical Microbiology. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18557"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T13:28:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T13:28:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11289"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75661"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4944","links":{"self":"https://app.